            <p>London Sept 8<hi rend="sup">th</hi> A M 5633<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I have the pleasure and satisfaction<lb/> of informing you of the safe arrival of Louisa<lb/> last Friday afternoon.  I will not call her<lb/> by her surname because she is for ever<lb/> separated from the worthless man that gave<lb/> it to her  My object in writing is not alone<lb/> to make known her return but also to apologize<lb/> and explain why I have not written before<lb/> for let me assure you that you would be the<lb/> last gentleman in the world that I would<lb/> neglect because more than five years ago<lb/> you convinced me that you would give <sic>an</sic><lb/> helping hand to assist a woman that was<lb/> upon an evil day united to a bad man<lb/> which has been fully demonstrated by<lb/> the part you have recently acted<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>I should have forgotten altogether<lb/> that I had received a letter from you and to<lb/> which you expected an answer had not<lb/> Louisa reminded me when she called to<lb/> see us last &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  I regretted that I had not<lb/> sent the expected answer but the fact is<lb/> I had forgotten all about it And now comes<lb/> the explanation why I am unfortunate<lb/>&#45;ly laboring under a nervous complaint<lb/> that impairs my memory to a serious<lb/> extent many things that were known<lb/> to me only a short time before soon become<lb/> effaced from my memory It is a rule<lb/> with me when I receive letters from abroad<lb/> or any distant place to answer them the<lb/> very next day unless I have some motive<lb/> for delay.  I must have had some particular<lb/> reason for delay in replying to your estee<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>med letter so afterwards I forgot all about<lb/> it.  The object I had at first in<lb/> view about six years back when I wrote<lb/> to that eminent&#91;&#63;&#93; man the Revd Isaac Leeser<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; so good as to reply to it bec&#45;<lb/>&#45;cause he was already confined to the Bed<lb/> from which he never arose<lb/></p>
            <p>You have faithfully earned out all<lb/> you undertook to do from the very beginning<lb/> and I believe you have done much more<lb/> because you have befriended her in a strange<lb/> country and you did not foresee that it would<lb/> be necessary for her to go to America at all<lb/> I may venture to say &#91;Hebrew&#93; May the<lb/> Lord bless you with &#91;Hebrew&#93; that you<lb/> may befriend others as you have done to<lb/> the one I thank and praise you for<lb/> I am Revd Sir<lb/> Your obliged Servant<lb/> David A Cohen<lb/> 22 Little Aln Street Goodmans Field<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>As the season is nearly approaching<lb/> for conveying our best wishes to those<lb/> we wish well I hope the God of Israel<lb/> may you a &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> Louisa sends her best respects<lb/> to yourself and family<lb/></p>
        </body>
